Crystal Langhorne matched a career-high with 34 points and added
15 rebounds, leading Maryland to a 82-63 win over the Lady Bears on Saturday night to eliminate Sophia Young
and the defending national champions from the NCAA Tournament.
article.headline: No repeat performance: Terps eliminate defending champ Baylor
article.linkText: No repeat performance: Terps eliminate defending champ Baylor
article.story:
ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- Of the 14 baskets Crystal Langhorne
made in another All-America performance, none was bigger than the
one that ended the first half.

Langhorne matched a career-high with 34 points and added 15
rebounds, leading No. 2 seeded Maryland to a 82-63 win over the
third-seeded Lady Bears on Saturday night to eliminate Sophia Young
and the defending national champions from the NCAA Tournament.

"They executed the game plan to perfection," Terrapins coach
Brenda Frese said. "They were hungry. They wanted to win. They
defended and rebounded better. It's just amazing to see that we
beat the defending national champions."

Langhorne made the play of the night at the halftime horn,
getting a layup that put the Terps ahead 35-28. The Terps inbounded
from halfcourt with 0.6 seconds on the clock, throwing all the way
to Langhorne underneath.

"I wasn't even going to go to the basket," Langhorne said.
"One of the coaches told me to get to the block and I'm saying,
'This isn't going to work."

It worked, all right.

Langhorne's layup was reviewed by game officials on video
monitors, but it stood. And that sucked much of the momentum from
Baylor after the Bears had pulled within 29-28 on a free throw by
Rachel Allison with 2:28 remaining in the first half.

"Sure, it took some momentum away," Baylor coach Kim
Mulkey-Robertson said. "That kind of deflates your bubble a little
bit."

The Terps (31-4) advanced to meet the winner of the late contest
between Utah and Boston College in Monday's Albuquerque Regional
final, with a berth in the Final Four at stake.

In a matchup of two of the country's best post players,
Langhorne, a 6-foot-2 sophomore, outplayed Young from the opening
tip. With their star at less than her best, the Bears (26-7)
couldn't survive one of their worst shooting nights of the season.
Baylor made just 33 percent (25-of-74).

"The effort was there. I believe our kids fought hard,"
Mulkey-Robertson said. "But I believe in complimenting the
opponent when they're better, and I thought Maryland was bigger and
better than us."

Young scored 26 points on 11-of-25 shooting but the Big 12's
career scoring and rebounding leader -- and the Most Valuable Player
from last year's Final Four -- got off to a horrible 1-for-7 start
in her final college game.

"My shot wasn't falling. I was just fading away too much,"
Young said.

Langhorne was everywhere, scoring the game's first eight points
as Maryland took control from the tipoff. They jumped to leads of
14-2 and 23-13. She had eight rebounds by the break, scoring three
times on putbacks.

"We kept pounding it in to her and they couldn't stop her,"
said Maryland's Marissa Coleman, who scored 15 points. "Our energy
was up from the tip and we intimidated our opponent. We kept it
going all game."

Kristi Toliver scored 12 points for the Terps, who start a
junior, two sophomores and two freshmen.

Anything seems possible now for Maryland under Frese, who in her
fourth year is one game from the program's first Final Four
appearance since 1989. The Terps were in the round of 16 for the
first time since 1992, and they want more.

"We thought we could win the national championship before every
one of our games," Langhorne said. "I think this just gives us
more confidence."

Langhorne's talent wasn't exactly classified information, but
compared to Young, she's been an under-the-radar star. Langhorne
was a first-team All-Atlantic Coast Conference selection who scored
30 points and made two key late baskets when Maryland beat St.
John's in the second round Tuesday.

"Langhorne was dominant," Mulkey-Robertson said. "We had
nobody to guard her."
